{{Advert|date=June 2018}} The '''Brumby Rocker''' is a [[rocking chair]] built by the '''Brumby Chair Factory''' of the '''Brumby Chair Company''' in [[Marietta, Georgia]], which operated between 1875 and 1942, or by its successor which started in 1972. They are big, sturdy, built to last, and difficult to manufacture. New ones cost about $1,000.<ref>In 2016, Brumby Rockers are listed at $995 at Houzz on the internet.</ref> [[Jimmy Carter]] brought five to the [[White House]].<ref name=winds>{{cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1989/03/07/us/marietta-journal-winds-of-change-rock-a-classic-rocking-chair.html |title=Marietta Journal; Winds of Change Rock A Classic Rocking Chair |author=Peter Applebome |publisher=[[New York Times]] |date=March 7, 1989 |accessdate=September 14, 2016}}</ref>
The chair is deliberately large, with large arms, seat, and "runners", and a very high back.<ref name=built>{{cite news|url=http://articles.latimes.com/1985-11-03/news/mn-3921_1_brumby-rocker |title=Built to Last a Lifetime : Brumby Chairs: The Rock of Ages |date=November 3, 1985|author=Bill Lohmann, [[United Press International]] |publisher=[[Los Angeles Times]] |accessdate=September 14, 2016}}</ref><ref name=rolling>{{cite news |url=http://articles.chicagotribune.com/1985-11-24/news/8503210613_1_brumby-family-carole-melson-brumby-jumbo-rocker |title=Brumby Rockers Keep Rolling With That Old-fashioned Quality |date=November 24, 1985|author=Bill Lohmann, [[United Press International]] |publisher=[[Chicago Tribune]] }}</ref>
<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.knoxnews.com/entertainment/columnists/joe-rosson/rosson-chair-company-still-doing-business-in-marietta-ga-ep-412491035-360113451.html |title=Rosson: Chair company still doing business in Marietta, Ga.}}</ref>
==History== James Remley Brumby was first owner of the Brumby Chair Factory.<ref name=nrhpdoc/>
The successor company started manufacturing in 1972. In 1989, the future was doubtful.<ref name=winds/>
==Buildings== The Brumby Chair Factory building (c. 1879), on Church Street{{refn|group=Note|167 Church Street, per NRHP doc; 67 Church Street per accompanying photos}} in Marietta, is a contributing building in the [[Northwest Marietta Historic District]].<ref name=nrhpdoc>{{cite web|url={{NRHP url|id=75000586}}|title=National Register of Historic Places Registration: Northwest Marietta Historic District|publisher=[[National Park Service]]|accessdate=September 11, 2016 |author=David T. Agnew and Elizabeth Z. Macgregor, |date=April 7, 1975 }} with {{NRHP url|id=75000586|photos=y|title=18 photos from 1974-75 (with #15 a photo of the factory)}}</ref> The Brumby-Sibley-Corley House, at 285 Kennesaw Avenue in the district, is the mid-Victorian house built by James Remley Brumby (photo #1).<ref name=nrhpdoc/>{{rp|5}}
