{{other uses|Wonders of the World (disambiguation)}} {{pp-pc1|small=yes}} {{refimprove article|date=February 2015}}
'''Eighth Wonder of the World''' is an unofficial [[title]] sometimes given to new buildings, structures, projects, or even designs that are deemed to be comparable to the seven [[Wonders of the World]].
==Candidates for the Eighth Wonder of the World== [[File:MitrePeakNZ.jpg|thumb|[[Mitre Peak, New Zealand|Mitre Peak]], in [[Milford Sound]], New Zealand]] ===Natural places=== * [[Burney Falls]] in [[California]]; called so by [[Theodore Roosevelt]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.burney-falls.com/|title=Welcome to Burney Falls!|website=Burney-falls.com|accessdate=4 November 2014}}</ref> * [[Deadvlei]] Clay Pan in [[Namibia]]<ref>[https://www.safari365.com/blog/is-deadvlei-the-8th-wonder-of-the-world]</ref> * [[Giant's Causeway]] in [[County Antrim]], [[Northern Ireland]]{{citation needed|date=October 2015}} * [[Gros Morne National Park]] in [[Newfoundland and Labrador|Newfoundland]], [[Canada]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.heritage.nf.ca/environment/geology.html |title=Geological Landscape: Newfoundland and Labrador Heritage |website=Heritage.nf.ca |date= |accessdate=January 18, 2013}}</ref> * [[Milford Sound]] in [[New Zealand]]; called so by [[Rudyard Kipling]]<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.nationalgeographic.com/photography/galleries/travelnewzealand/ |date=June 19, 2006 |work=National Geographic |title=Travel New Zealand |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20060619091040/http://www.nationalgeographic.com/photography/galleries/travelnewzealand/ |archivedate=June 19, 2006 |df= }}</ref> * [[Natural Bridge (Virginia)]], so dubbed by [[William Jennings Bryan]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dcr.virginia.gov/state_parks/nat.shtml |title=Natural Tunnel State Park |website=Dcr.virginia.gov |date=December 2012|accessdate=2013-01-18}}</ref> * [[Niagara Falls]], between the [[Provinces and territories of Canada|province]] of [[Ontario]] and the [[New York (state)|state of New York]].<ref>{{cite news|title=The Niagara Mill-Seat|url=https://www.nytimes.com/1853/02/10/archives/the-niagara-millseat.html|accessdate=31 January 2018|work=New York Times|date=February 10, 1853|page=4}}</ref> * The [[Okavango Delta]] in [[Botswana]]{{citation needed|date=March 2018}} * [[Pink and White Terraces]] in New Zealand, prior to their wrongly assumed destruction in the [[Mount Tarawera#1886 eruption|1886 eruption of Mount Tarawera]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.nzherald.co.nz/nz/news/article.cfm?c_id=1&objectid=10703655|title=Remains of Pink Terraces discovered|work=The New Zealand Herald|accessdate=4 November 2014}}</ref> In 2017 researchers using a lost 1959 survey finally mapped the Pink and White terrace locations.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bunn|first=Rex|last2=Nolden|first2=Sascha|date=2017-06-07|title=Forensic cartography with Hochstetter’s 1859 Pink and White Terraces survey: Te Otukapuarangi and Te Tarata|url=https://dx.doi.org/10.1080/03036758.2017.1329748|journal=Journal of the Royal Society of New Zealand|volume=0|issue=0|pages=1–18|doi=10.1080/03036758.2017.1329748|issn=0303-6758}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Bunn and Nolden|first=Rex and Sascha|date=December 2016|title=Te Tarata and Te Otukapuarangi: Reverse engineering Hochstetter’s Lake Rotomahana Survey to map the Pink and White Terrace locations|url=https://ojs.victoria.ac.nz/jnzs/article/view/3988/3555|journal=Journal of New Zealand Studies|volume=NS23|pages=37–53|via=}}</ref> * [[Torres del Paine National Park]], [[Chile]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.virtualtourist.com/8thwonder|title=8th Wonder of the World |access-date=1 November 2013 |author= |date=1 November 2013 |website=www.virtualtourist.com}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.advfn.com/news_Chiles-Torres-del-Paine-National-Park-Selected-as_59836588.html |title=Chile's Torres del Paine National Park Selected as 8th Wonder of the World by VirtualTourist Voters |access-date=1 November 2013 |author= |date=1 November 2013 |website=www.advfn.com}}</ref> * The great [[wildebeest]] migration in the [[Maasai Mara]], Kenya and [[Serengeti]], Tanzania<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.iserengeti.com/wildebeest-great-migration.html |title=The Great Wildebeest Migration, Serengeti and Masai Mara |website=Iserengeti.com |date= |accessdate=2013-01-18 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130106210427/http://www.iserengeti.com/wildebeest-great-migration.html |archivedate=2013-01-06 |df= }}</ref> * [[Uluru]] in [[Australia]].{{citation needed|date=July 2013}}
