The '''[http://sath.org Society for Accessible Travel & Hospitality]''', or SATH, is a [[New York City|New York]] based [[non-profit organization]] founded in 1976 and dedicated to the promotion of [[accessibility]] in the travel & tourism industries. SATH's mission is "to raise awareness of the needs of all travelers with disabilities, remove physical and attitudinal barriers to free access and expand travel opportunities in the United States and abroad."  Through lobbying and education efforts, the Society has been credited with helping secure such acts as the [[Americans With Disabilities Act]].

SATH presents a number of awards including the Murray Award<ref name="hn">{{Cite web|url=http://www.hospitalitynet.org/news/4018210.search?query=%22society+for+accessible+travel+%26+hospitality%22|title=John Q. Hammons Hotels, Inc. to Receive Murray Award From the Society for Accessible Travel and Hospitality (SATH)|accessdate=2008-02-21|publisher=Hospitality Net|date=2004-01-13}}</ref> and Access to Freedom Award,<ref name="ac">{{Cite web|url=http://www.hotelmotel.com/hotelmotel/News+Wire/Flora-honored-with-Access-to-Freedom-Award/ArticleStandard/Article/detail/484925|title=Flora Honored with 'Access to Freedom' Award|accessdate=2008-02-21|date=2008-01-16|work=[[Hotel & Motel Management]]}}</ref> which are given to industry practitioners that accommodate the needs of disabled travelers.

