'''Utian''' (also '''Miwok–Costanoan''', previously '''Mutsun''') is a [[Indigenous languages of the Americas|family of indigenous languages]] spoken in [[Northern California]], [[United States]]. The [[Miwok]] and [[Ohlone]] peoples both spoke languages of the Utian language family. It has recently been argued that the Utian languages and [[Yawelmani language|Yokuts languages]] are sub-families of the [[Yok-Utian]] language family ([[Catherine Callaghan|Callaghan]] 1997, 2001; Golla 2007:76-77). Utian and Yokutsan have traditionally been considered part of the [[Penutian languages|Penutian]] language phylum (Goddard 1996:313-319; Mithun 1999; Shipley 1978:82-85).
All Utian languages are severely [[endangered language|endangered]].
